# TODO / Improvement Backlog
# Written 2026-06-09 (session: app-wide improvements). Safe to hand to a future
# session — each item is self-contained. Top 20 ranked by value-for-effort.

## Top 20 improvement ideas

 1. PDF report export — branded, print-ready report (cover page, contents,
    matrices, register, treatment roadmap). Today only Word/Excel copy exists.
 2. Multi-assessment manager — home screen listing saved assessments with
    open/rename/delete. localStorage currently holds ONE assessment; switching
    projects risks silent overwrite.
 3. Undo/redo (Ctrl+Z) — scoring grids are click-heavy and a stray click on a
    score bar or "Clear All" is destructive.
 4. Interactive dashboard matrix — click a risk-matrix cell to filter the risk
    register to those risks; click-through from summary tiles.
 5. Reviewer workflow — per-risk comments with author/timestamp, and a
    review/sign-off status per section (draft → reviewed → issued).
 6. Assessment compare/diff — load two saved JSON files and show risk deltas
    (pre/post design change, year-on-year review).
 7. Treatment prioritisation — capture indicative cost + effort per measure,
    auto-build a quick-win / planned / long-term roadmap table for the report.
 8. Executive summary auto-draft — generate narrative text from the data (top
    risks, crime trend, posture) as a starting point for the assessor.
 9. QA / completeness gate before export — checklist flagging unscored
    threats, missing ALARP justifications, empty required context fields.
10. Photo attachments on POIs and Existing Controls (site walkaround
    evidence), included in Word/PDF export.
11. Tablet/mobile site-survey mode — POI capture optimised for touch on a
    walkaround; the desktop layout is dense on small screens.
12. Offline crime-data snapshot — store fetched Police.uk data inside the
    saved assessment so reports are reproducible later (data changes monthly).
13. Non-UK mode — Police.uk only covers England/Wales/NI; allow manual crime
    stats entry + international threat-level sources for overseas sites.
14. Proper accounts/backend — replace APP_PASSWORD + GitHub-token-in-browser
    with real auth and server-side persistence (also fixes: plaintext password
    in session cookie, secret baked into client bundle by build.js).
15. Org template library — save/share company-standard criteria text, threat
    sets and treatment libraries as versioned template files.
16. Full WCAG AA pass — contrast on score chips, focus trap inside modals,
    screen-reader labels on score bars, aria-live for toasts.
17. Keyboard bulk scoring — extend existing 1-5/arrow keys with "apply to
    whole row/column" and copy-down, for large grids.
18. Performance: split the 616KB single file (lazy-load Leaflet, html2canvas,
    crime tab) for faster first paint; consider build step producing chunks.
19. Automated tests + CI — Playwright smoke test per tab + export functions
    (a single 7,800-line file regresses easily); GitHub Action on PR.
20. In-app help/onboarding — "?" tooltips per section explaining methodology
    terms (TA, DBT, ALARP) for less-experienced assessors; link methodology.

## Questions for James (answers will steer the backlog)
- Is this single-assessor (just you) or will colleagues use it? (drives #2,
  #5, #14, #15)
- Do clients receive the Word export, or would a branded PDF be the primary
  deliverable? (drives #1, #8)
- Any non-UK / overseas sites in the pipeline? (drives #13)
- Should saved client data live anywhere other than the browser + your GitHub
  repo? Compliance/GDPR view on projects/ folder living in git history? (#14)

## Known security items (deliberately not changed without sign-off)
- middleware.js stores the plaintext APP_PASSWORD in the session cookie —
  switch to a hashed/opaque token (needs matching change in api/db.js +
  api/report.py).
- build.js bakes APP_PASSWORD into the obfuscated client JS via
  __API_SECRET__ — recoverable by anyone with the file; rely on the session
  cookie instead.
- projects/ (client assessment data) is committed to git history — confirm
  this is intended; consider a private data repo.

